**Untested:** `collectSpeechTargets`, `rangeForNormalizedOffsets` (private), `useSpeechFollow`.

**Edge cases:**
- `collectSpeechTargets`: container element whose children match the selector (e.g. a `<div class="key-ideas">` containing `<li>`) — must skip the container per the "skipping containers whose matched children carry the same text" comment, keep only leaf matches.
- Elements with only whitespace text content → excluded.
- `root === null` → returns `{ texts: [], elements: [] }`.
- `rangeForNormalizedOffsets`: offsets spanning multiple text nodes (e.g. text broken up by inline `<em>`/`<strong>`), `start === end` → `null`, offsets beyond the text length → `null`, leading/collapsed whitespace correctly skipped when computing normalized positions.

```ts
describe('collectSpeechTargets', () => {
  it('returns empty arrays for a null root', () => {
    expect(collectSpeechTargets(null, 'p')).toEqual({ texts: [], elements: [] })
  })
  it('skips a container whose children already match the selector', () => {
    document.body.innerHTML = '<div class="key-ideas"><h2>Title</h2><li>Point</li></div>'
    const { texts } = collectSpeechTargets(document.body, '.key-ideas, li')
    expect(texts).toEqual(['Point']) // container itself excluded
  })
  it('excludes whitespace-only elements', () => {
    document.body.innerHTML = '<p>   </p><p>Real text</p>'
    const { texts } = collectSpeechTargets(document.body, 'p')
    expect(texts).toEqual(['Real text'])
  })
})
```

`useSpeechFollow` is a hook with DOM side effects (`scrollIntoView`, `classList`, CSS Highlight API) — best covered with `@testing-library/react`'s `renderHook`, mocking `Element.prototype.scrollIntoView` and `CSS.highlights` (jsdom lacks the Custom Highlight API entirely, so `canHighlight` will always be `false` in tests unless polyfilled — worth asserting the graceful-degradation path explicitly, since it's real production behavior on older Firefox/Safari too).

